video_thumbnail:
Dexter Community Education
August 21 at 8:28 PM ·

Woo-hoo! We celebrated the end of nine(!) successful weeks of Camp Dexter today with a visit from the Kona Ice snow cone truck! Camp Dexter looked a lot different this year but it was still a lot of fun! Mrs. Paula planned lots of fabulous themes and craft ideas and we enjoyed some of the traditional camp activities, including tie-dye, magic milk, slime day and visits by the birds and reptiles from the Leslie Science Center. Thank you to the 48 families who entrusted us with their children and great job to the campers who continually washed their hands, wore their masks indoors and remained healthy all summer. Thank you to our adult staff, including: Paula, Mandi, Beth, Dawn, Mr. B, Theresa and Michelle for staying safe and healthy so these kids could have a summer camp experience. We'll share more camp photos with you on Monday. For more info on Camp Dexter, call Dexter Community Ed at 424-4180 or email keithj@dexterschools.org

post_text:
Current Dexter families: if you moved out of the District since last year but still want to attend DCS, today is the last day to apply for SOC status. It’s a one-page app for each student.

Schools of Choice Second Application Window
The Dexter Community Schools district is a limited schools of choice district. This means that we have two, two-week application windows during which families can apply to attend as school of choice students for the following fall. The second window is open July 20th through 31st. We can only accept applications during this window. For the application form and details about how to apply, please visit https://www.dexterschools.org/district/choice.

If you are trying to fax in an application and are having any difficulty, please try 734-424-4108.

It has been a tradition at Anchor (formerly Cornerstone) Elementary for Ms. VanHouten's 1st grade class to perform their Patriotic Concert honoring veterans, all military, firefighters, police officers and emergency personnel. The students sang songs, read poems and honored all those present.

This year's concert wasn't able to happen due to the school closure, so the students and their family members put together this heartwarming video of the 1st graders singing, "The Star-Spangled Banner." Enjoy!

Excellence 4 Dexter Students (E4DS) and the Educational Foundation of Dexter (EFD) are proud to announce a new partnership, beginning in May 2020. Our merged organization will together carry forward the missions and values of both entities under the Educational Foundation of Dexter’s name, with “Excellence for Dexter Students” as the guiding principle. We are excited to unite the skill sets and volunteer energy of our committed board members and feel confident that this alignment will allow us to do even more to support excellence in our school community. We move forward as one foundation, supporting one school community. #E4DS

post_text:
Music Lovers...Chrome has a very cool Music Lab that students can explore to learn more about music. There's no log in, just go to the link and click on any of the images to try out the experiment. There's a yellow circle with a question mark at the top right corner of each experiment screen. If you click on that, it will explain what the experiment is exploring. (Teacher tip: let your kids explore, then ask them what they think is happening *before* you click on the explanation.)

https://musiclab.chromeexperiments.com/Experiments

Sharing info re: the Michigan Medicine SPARK Study:
--------------------------------
Have you heard about SPARK? SPARK is already the largest autism research study, but we are just getting started!

What is SPARK?
We are a growing community of individuals, families, and researchers on a mission to speed up the understanding of autism. Our aims are to:
- Collect DNA and information through surveys from 50,000 people with autism and both of their parents.
- Share that data with researchers.
- Make breakthroughs that were never before possible.
- Return our findings to you.

SPARK is sponsored by the Simons Foundation Autism Research Initiative (SFARI) and Michigan Medicine is one of more than…
